---
import CaseStudy from '../../layouts/CaseStudy.astro';
---

<CaseStudy
  title="Redesigning the product development lifecycle"
  eyebrow="Branch · 2025–2026"
  summary="A four-phase operating model with named DACI ownership, paired problem and technical solution briefs, mandatory success metrics before Build, and a 90-day Invest, Iterate, or Deprecate decision loop. Adopted across Product, Design, Engineering, and PMM."
  role="Sr. Director of Product Experience"
  duration="Q3 2025 to Q2 2026"
  team="Product, Design, Engineering, PMM, Marketing"
  outcome="Operating model adopted org-wide"
>
  <h2>The problem we kept paying for</h2>

  <p>
    Branch was shipping product, but Define was a black hole. Problems got framed by PM
    alone, designers entered at ticket assignment instead of at problem framing,
    engineers reacted to scoped solutions instead of shaping them, and analytics showed
    up after launch instead of before. The cost of this wasn't just velocity. It was
    that we'd ship features without success metrics, then quietly accumulate them into
    maintenance burden engineering called crushing.
  </p>

  <p>
    The biggest tell was the gap between launch and measurement. Almost nothing that
    shipped had a dashboard plan defined before Build started. So we couldn't tell which
    features were working. So we couldn't make Invest, Iterate, or Deprecate decisions.
    So nothing got deprecated. So the system got heavier every quarter.
  </p>

  <p>
    I was asked to lead the redesign of how Branch builds product. Not a process
    document. A real operating model that Product, Design, Engineering, and PMM would
    actually adopt.
  </p>

  <h2>The four-phase model</h2>

  <p>
    The framework I built has four phases that every initiative moves through in
    sequence:
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose my-12 grid md:grid-cols-4 gap-4">
    {[
      {
        n: '01',
        name: 'Discover',
        desc: 'Problem framing with the full triad (PM, PD, EM) in the room from the start. Customer research, technical context, design exploration. Exit: a problem brief everyone signed.',
      },
      {
        n: '02',
        name: 'Plan',
        desc: 'Paired problem brief and technical solution brief. Defined success metrics. Dashboard plan. 30/60/90-day review scheduled. Analytics engaged. Exit: a measurable plan.',
      },
      {
        n: '03',
        name: 'Build',
        desc: 'SDLC runs inside this phase. PD active in hi-fi and QA, not handed off at ticket creation. Customer design partner engaged on significant initiatives.',
      },
      {
        n: '04',
        name: 'Measure',
        desc: '30, 60, and 90-day reviews against the metrics defined at Plan. Triad reconvenes. Invest, Iterate, or Deprecate decision. Loop back to Discover.',
      },
    ].map((phase) => (
      <div class="p-6 border border-ink/15 bg-cream-warm/50">
        <p class="font-mono text-xs text-orange uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">{phase.n}</p>
        <p class="font-display text-2xl text-ink mb-3">{phase.name}<span class="text-orange">.</span></p>
        <p class="text-sm text-ink-soft leading-snug">{phase.desc}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <p>
    Design and Customer Proximity run through all four phases as standing threads, not
    as one-time gates. Design is never "started" at ticket assignment. Customer contact
    is a calendar commitment with defined minimums per phase (three in Discover, one in
    Plan, design partner in Build for significant initiatives, two in Measure).
  </p>

  <p>
    PDLC governs initiative-level work. SDLC runs inside Build. Iteration on existing
    features routes back through Measure, Discover, Plan, Build, not straight back to
    Build.
  </p>

  <h2>The three non-negotiables</h2>

  <p>
    The framework introduced a lot. To make it real instead of aspirational, I named
    three things as non-negotiable starting Q2 2026.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>The triad engages from Discover, not from Plan.</strong> Technical
    feasibility and design implications shape the problem brief itself. Loops back from
    Measure re-engage the triad before returning to Build. This is the single change
    that did the most to fix Define as a black hole.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Measurement is the spine.</strong> Every initiative entering Plan has defined
    success metrics, a dashboard plan, and a 30/60/90 review scheduled. Dashboards exist
    at launch. Analytics is engaged at Plan, not at launch.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Invest, Iterate, or Deprecate decisions happen at 90 days, documented, with
    feed-forward to Discover.</strong> Every significant initiative gets a formal
    decision. Features without decisions don't accumulate silently into maintenance
    burden.
  </p>

  <h2>DACI as the ownership model</h2>

  <p>
    For each phase, I defined who is the Driver, Approver, Contributor, and Informed.
    The model is adapted at the pod level (each pod revisits its charter with KPIs,
    personas, target users, and pod-specific DACI), but the overall pattern is fixed.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose my-10 overflow-x-auto">
    <table class="w-full border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-ink/20">
          <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-ink-muted">Phase</th>
          <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-ink-muted">Gate owner</th>
          <th class="text-left py-3 px-4 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-ink-muted">Co-drivers</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="font-display">
        <tr class="border-b border-ink/10">
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink">Discover</td>
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink-soft">PM</td>
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink-soft">PD, EM, Research</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-ink/10">
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink">Plan</td>
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink-soft">PM + EM</td>
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink-soft">PD, Analytics, PMM</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-ink/10">
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink">Build</td>
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink-soft">EM then PM</td>
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink-soft">PD, QA, Customer design partner</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink">Measure</td>
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink-soft">VP Product</td>
          <td class="py-4 px-4 text-ink-soft">PM, PD, EM, Analytics</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2>The structural gaps I named alongside the framework</h2>

  <p>
    A framework is only as strong as the infrastructure supporting it. As part of the
    PDLC rollout, I named four parallel commitments leadership had to make for the
    operating model to actually work.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Single source of truth for specs.</strong> Designate one system as
    authoritative. Migration-forward policy. New initiatives use it Day 1.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Functioning deprecation process.</strong> Quarterly Feature Health Review.
    PM proposes, VP Product approves Reinvest, Maintain, or Deprecate. Deprecation
    requires 90-day customer notice, migration path, sunset date. Without this,
    AI-accelerated build would only compound the maintenance burden.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Research access infrastructure.</strong> Weekly customer touchpoint cadence
    (calendar commitment). Named research coordinator per team. Great Question as
    designated repository. Searchable, accessible to all of proddev.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Monthly PDLC Health Review.</strong> A standing leadership review of whether
    gates are respected, measurement is happening, pods are stuck, friction is surfacing.
    Not a status meeting. The mechanism that keeps the framework from ossifying.
  </p>

  <h2>The rollout sequence</h2>

  <p>
    I designed the rollout to land in four steps, with the Monthly PDLC Health Review
    running throughout.
  </p>

  <div class="not-prose my-10 space-y-6">
    {[
      {
        when: 'May',
        what: 'Pod charter revisions. Each pod revisits its charter with KPIs, personas, target users, and adapted DACI. Pod leads (EM + PM) drive. AI tooling rolls out to proddev in parallel.',
      },
      {
        when: 'June',
        what: 'Triad engagement from Discover begins for all new initiatives. Sanctioned and unsanctioned AI blurring patterns communicated and enforced. Monthly PDLC Health Review begins.',
      },
      {
        when: 'Q3',
        what: 'Every initiative entering Plan has defined success metrics, dashboard plan, 30/60/90 review scheduled. Analytics owner engaged at Plan. First cohort reaches Measure with full framework applied.',
      },
      {
        when: 'Q4',
        what: 'Feature Health Review running quarterly. First cohort of Invest, Iterate, or Deprecate decisions documented. Loop to Discover operational.',
      },
    ].map((step) => (
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-6 pb-6 border-b border-ink/10">
        <div class="md:col-span-2">
          <p class="font-mono text-xs text-orange uppercase tracking-[0.15em]">{step.when}</p>
        </div>
        <div class="md:col-span-10 text-ink-soft">{step.what}</div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <p>
    The maturity target is Level 2 across all phases by end of 2026, per QBR commitment.
    Level 3 work begins in 2027 with foundations holding.
  </p>

  <h2>Three decisions for VP alignment</h2>

  <p>
    When I brought the framework to VP Product and VP Engineering for sign-off, I
    isolated three decisions that only they could make. Everything else could be adjusted
    by the Director, EM, and Product leads group.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>1. Model adoption.</strong> Do we adopt the four-phase model with Design and
    Customer Proximity as continuous threads, governing initiative-level work, with SDLC
    running inside Build?
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>2. Q2 non-negotiables.</strong> Do we commit to the four Q2 fundamentals?
    Measurement spine at Plan. Triad engagement from Discover. 90-day Invest, Iterate,
    or Deprecate decisions. AI tool use at the phase level with sanctioned vs.
    unsanctioned patterns.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>3. AI mandate alignment.</strong> The PDLC operationalizes the QBR's pillar
    two (AI adoption as measured expectation). What is the leadership-defined mandate
    and metric? The PDLC document doesn't define it. It needs to align with it.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this case study</h2>

  <p>
    Operating model design is the work most design leaders never get to do, and the
    work that most differentiates a Sr. Director from a VP. It's not about choosing a
    process framework. It's about diagnosing the structural reason a company keeps
    shipping things it can't measure, designing the cross-functional architecture that
    fixes it, and getting Product, Engineering, and PMM to actually adopt it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Design upstream into discovery. Measurement as the spine. The loop closed at 90
    days. That's the leverage.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
